    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-logarithms-of-powers-and-roots" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Logarithms of Powers and Roots</title>
        <objectives component="outcomes">
            <introduction>
                <p>
                <dl>
                    <li>
                        <title>Strand</title>
                        <p>
                            1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                        <p>
                            1.2 Indices and Logarithms
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                        <p>
                            Apply common logarithms in multiplication, division, powers and roots of numbers
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Grade Level</title>
                        <p>
                            10
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                        <p>
                            40 minutes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
                </p>
                <p component="lesson-plan">
                    <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that logarithms convert powers into multiplication and roots into division, and recognize the power law <m>\log(a^b) = b \times \log(a)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Use logarithm tables and the power law to evaluate expressions involving powers and roots.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply logarithms of powers and roots to solve real-world problems such as finding side lengths and volumes.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    </p>
                </p>
            </introduction>
        </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
            <!-- Link to blurb -->
            <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

            <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
                <sidebyside>
                    <p>
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/logarithms-of-powers-and-roots.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/step-by-step-guide_logarithms-of-powers-and-roots.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                    </p>
                </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </axiom>
        <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery / Engage &amp; Explore</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To explore logarithm tables and discover patterns in finding logarithms of powers and roots.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Anchor Learning Experience: Exploring Logarithms of Powers and Roots</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Students use calculators and math reasoning to explore expressions involving logarithms of powers and roots. They calculate <m>\log(10000)</m>, rewrite it as <m>\log(10^4)</m>, and apply the logarithmic law <m>\log(a^b) = b \times \log(a)</m>. They then try <m>\log(100)</m>, <m>\log(1000000)</m>, <m>\log(\sqrt{100})</m>, and <m>\log(\sqrt[3]{1000})</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Discussion Questions:</alert>
                <ul>
                    <li><p>What do you observe when applying logarithms to square and cube roots?</p></li>
                    <li><p>Why does <m>\log(\sqrt{100})</m> give half of <m>\log(100)</m>?</p></li>
                    <li><p>What general rule can you form for logarithms and powers?</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Allow students to use calculators freely. Encourage students to express numbers as powers of 10. Ask probing questions: <q>What pattern do you notice?</q>, <q>How does the exponent relate to the logarithm?</q>. Guide students to see that <m>\log(a^b) = b \times \log(a)</m>. Help students recognize that roots are fractional powers (<m>\sqrt{a} = a^{1/2}</m>). Use student discoveries as a bridge to formal logarithm laws.
            </p>
        </axiom>


        <p xml:id="auto_gr7hxng2">
            Logarithms can be used to simplify calculations involving powers and roots by converting exponentiation into multiplication and roots into division.
        </p>

        <activity xml:id="auto_f95cjpci">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_sfuvcp1l">
                    <term>Material needed:</term> 
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_6f1ykk8i">
                    <ul xml:id="auto_gu7mxok1">
                        <li xml:id="auto_mgyuond6"><p xml:id="auto_rdtyuyv9">Pen and paper</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_mwyq9f8p"><p xml:id="auto_jyvgtzqc">A scientific calculator</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_2r85axn0">
                    <term>Instructions:</term>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_khojwmep">
                    Use your calculator and math reasoning to solve the following expressions involving logarithms:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xl49cwfp">
                    <me>\log(10000)</me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_yfe1pkui">
                    Now rewrite <m>10000</m> as a power of <m>10</m>:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ytqslwnl">
                    <me>\log(10000) = \log(10^4)</me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nqu0yszc">
                    Apply the logarithmic law: <me>\log(a^b) = b \times \log(a)</me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9schvrwe">
                    <me>\log(10^4) = 4 \times \log(10)</me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_dvfnv63u">
                    <me>= 4 \times 1 = 4</me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_qh75lgun">
                    Try the following:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9dbakcu7">
                    <ul xml:id="auto_vg3917w5">
                        <li xml:id="auto_ll7c99hz"><p xml:id="auto_r539nqp4"><me>\log(100)</me></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_jwidddq9"><p xml:id="auto_j4efvdfk"><me>\log(1000000)</me></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_c701vptc"><p xml:id="auto_axkfrk8v"><me>\log(\sqrt{100})</me></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_y6p2i5zs"><p xml:id="auto_9sjb0beg"><me>\log(\sqrt[3]{1000})</me></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_2yfog3um">
                    <ul xml:id="auto_1eqruzh3">
                        <li xml:id="auto_4db73tu7"><p xml:id="auto_vtk7gmh7">What do you observe when applying logarithms to square and cube roots?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_cfsczc3l"><p xml:id="auto_s5au6bpe">Why does <me>\log(\sqrt{100})</me> give half of <me>\log(100)</me>?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_1toxkbc5"><p xml:id="auto_a373u2gd">What general rule can you form for logarithms and powers?</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <insight>
            <p xml:id="auto_7u15ha6g">
                Logarithms help simplify calculations involving powers and roots.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_iglvb2ri">
                For example: <m>\log(a^b) = b \times \log(a)</m>, and <m>\log(\sqrt{a}) = \frac{1}{2} \times \log(a)</m>.
            </p>
        </insight>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction / Explain</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To formalize the rules for logarithms of powers and roots.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Key Takeaways:</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>1. Logarithms Simplify Powers and Roots:</alert> Logarithms help simplify calculations involving powers and roots by converting multiplication and division into addition and subtraction, and powers and roots into multiplication and division.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>2. Logarithm of a Power:</alert> When you take the logarithm of a number raised to a power, you can bring the exponent down as a multiplier:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\log(a^b) = b \times \log(a)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Examples:
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>\log(10^4) = 4 \times \log(10) = 4 \times 1 = 4</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log(2^3) = 3 \times \log(2) = 3 \times 0.3010 = 0.9030</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log(5^6) = 6 \times \log(5) = 6 \times 0.6990 = 4.194</m></p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>3. Logarithm of a Root:</alert> Roots can be expressed as fractional powers. For example, <m>\sqrt{a} = a^{1/2}</m> and <m>\sqrt[3]{a} = a^{1/3}</m>. Therefore:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\log(\sqrt{a}) = \log(a^{1/2}) = \frac{1}{2} \times \log(a)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\log(\sqrt[3]{a}) = \log(a^{1/3}) = \frac{1}{3} \times \log(a)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Examples:
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>\log(\sqrt{100}) = \frac{1}{2} \times \log(100) = \frac{1}{2} \times 2 = 1</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log(\sqrt[3]{1000}) = \frac{1}{3} \times \log(1000) = \frac{1}{3} \times 3 = 1</m></p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>4. Why This Works:</alert> The power law works because logarithms are exponents. When we raise a number to a power and then take the logarithm, we are essentially counting how many times we multiply the base.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>5. Practical Applications:</alert> These laws allow us to calculate large powers without direct multiplication, find roots of numbers using logarithm tables, solve exponential equations, and simplify complex calculations in science and engineering.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Clarify that the exponent <q>comes down</q> as a multiplier. Emphasize that roots are fractional powers. Show the connection: <m>\sqrt{a} = a^{1/2}</m>, <m>\sqrt[3]{a} = a^{1/3}</m>.
            </p>
        </axiom>


        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    We can also use logarithms to simplify calculations that don't directly involve logarithms.
                    For example, computing <m>2^{20}</m> by multiplying would be lot of work.
                    Approximate <m>2^{20}</m> using logarithms.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Note that <m>\text{Antilog}(\log 2^{20}) = 2^{20}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Then <m>\log 2^{20} = 20 \times \log 2 \approx 20 \times 0.3010 = 6.020 \approx 6</m> using logarithm tables.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Then <m>2^{20} = \text{Antilog}(\log 2^{20}) \approx \text{Antilog}(6) = 10^6 = 1000000</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (Remark: The exact value is 1048576.)
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To apply the power and root laws of logarithms to evaluate expressions.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students work through worked examples: evaluating <m>(23.5)^4</m>, <m>\sqrt[3]{524.8}</m>, and <m>(78.5)^3</m> using logarithm tables and the power law. They follow a systematic step-by-step process: take the logarithm, apply the power law, look up values in tables, and find the antilogarithm.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> The teacher monitors students, guiding them through the step-by-step process and checking their table readings for accuracy.
            </p>
        </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_3pooh8v2">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_2waisw5k">
                    Evaluate <m>(23.5)^4</m> using logarithm tables.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_nfyeqhs7">
                    Find the logarithm of <m>23.5</m> from the logarithm table:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ihmbg8vw">
                    <me>
                        \log 23.5 = 1.3711
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_bd7v0m53">
                    Multiply by the exponent <m>4</m>:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_oj4ej7vc">
                    <me>
                        1.3711 \times 4 = 5.4844
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_uumgarzn">
                    Find the antilogarithm of <m>5.4844</m>:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_uvt42atb">
                    <me>
                        \text{Antilog} (5.4844) \approx 304000
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_0307v0j7">
                    Thus, <m>(23.5)^4 \approx 304000</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="auto_ufbipct1">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_4c2a5mne">
                    Evaluate <m>\sqrt[3]{524.8}</m> using logarithm tables.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_06e9pxda">
                    Find the logarithm of <m>524.8</m> from the logarithm table:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_w5tbvxp6">
                    <me>
                        \log 524.8 = 2.7200
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_p4hyoez7">
                    Divide the logarithm by <m>3</m> (since it is a cube root):
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_0y23nw7m">
                    <me>
                        \frac{2.7200}{3} = 0.9067
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_hvc4gkvw">
                    Find the antilogarithm of <m>0.9067</m>:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_qcvkh7qy">
                    <me>
                        \text{Antilog} (0.9067) \approx 8.1
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_eoeue1jx">
                    Thus, <m>\sqrt[3]{524.8} \approx 8.1</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 4: Assessment / Evaluate (Exit Ticket)</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 5 minutes
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To formatively assess individual student understanding.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students complete exit ticket questions individually:
                <ol>
                    <li><p>The volume of a cube is 79,507 cubic centimetres. Use logarithms to find the length of one side. (Hint: Volume <m>= \text{side}^3</m>, so side <m>= \sqrt[3]{\text{Volume}}</m>)</p></li>
                    <li><p>Compute <m>(78.5)^3</m> using logarithms.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Compute <m>(254.6)^4</m> using logarithms.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Collect and review exit tickets to gauge student understanding and identify misconceptions for the next lesson.
            </p>
        </axiom>
        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Exit Ticket Answer Key</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Question 1:</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Let side <m>= s</m>, then <m>s^3 = 79{,}507</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>s = \sqrt[3]{79{,}507}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\log(s) = \frac{1}{3} \times \log(79{,}507)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\log(79{,}507) = 4.9004</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\log(s) = 4.9004 \div 3 = 1.6335</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>s = \text{antilog}(1.6335) = 43.0</m> cm
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Question 2:</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\log\!\left((78.5)^3\right) = 3 \times \log(78.5) = 3 \times 1.8949 = 5.6847</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>(78.5)^3 = \text{antilog}(5.6847) \approx 484{,}000</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Question 3:</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\log\!\left((254.6)^4\right) = 4 \times \log(254.6) = 4 \times 2.4059 = 9.6236</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>(254.6)^4 = \text{antilog}(9.6236) \approx 4{,}200{,}000{,}000</m>
            </p>
        </axiom>
        <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />

